*Injecting Spring Security beans as method parameters

  OfficeFloor registers every bean in the Spring application context as a managed object available by
  type.  Spring Security beans — including <<<UserDetailsService>>>, <<<PasswordEncoder>>>, and the
  <<<SecurityFilterChain>>> itself — are therefore available as plain parameters with no annotation:

%{snippet|file=${basedir}/src/main/resources/officefloor/rest/security/bean.GET.yml|ignoreDownloadError=false}

%{snippet|id=tutorial|file=${basedir}/src/main/java/net/officefloor/tutorial/springrestsecurity/SecurityBeanService.java|ignoreDownloadError=false}

  This is the same mechanism used for any Spring <<<@Service>>> or <<<@Component>>> — there is no
  special handling for security beans.



*Method-level security annotations — <<<@PreAuthorize>>>, <<<@Secured>>>, <<<@RolesAllowed>>>

  Spring Security's AOP-based method security annotations work by wrapping Spring-managed beans in
  a proxy.  OfficeFloor service classes are plain Java objects, not Spring beans, so the AOP proxy
  is never applied and these annotations have no effect on them.

  The recommended approach is to declare access rules in the <<<SecurityFilterChain>>> by URL, as
  shown in the security configuration above.  Alternatively, a service method can receive the
  <<<Authentication>>> or <<<UserDetails>>> object and perform the role check programmatically:

+--
public void service(Authentication authentication, ObjectResponse<String> response) {
    if (!authentication.getAuthorities().stream()
            .map(GrantedAuthority::getAuthority)
            .anyMatch("ROLE_ADMIN"::equals)) {
        throw new AccessDeniedException("Admin role required");
    }
    response.send("Admin content");
}
+--

  If the service method delegates to a Spring bean, <<<@PreAuthorize>>> on the bean method works
  normally because the bean is Spring-managed and its proxy is active.



*Testing

  Tests use the standard Spring Security test support.  No OfficeFloor-specific test utilities are
  required.

  <<<@WithMockUser>>> creates a synthetic user in the <<<SecurityContext>>> without touching
  <<<UserDetailsService>>>.  <<<@WithUserDetails("user")>>> instead loads the real <<<UserDetails>>>
  object from the configured <<<UserDetailsService>>> — useful when the service method inspects
  granted authorities or other fields populated by the real implementation.

  The tests cover all five endpoints and both test annotations:

